ttribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old form of   Gladys  , of uncertain derivation."],"variants":[{"name":"Gwladys","meanings":["Old form of   Gladys  , of uncertain derivation."]}]},{"name":"Verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]},{"name":"Dafydd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>David</b> . In widespread use during the Middle Ages, it was later largely replaced by the English form, but since the late 19th century it has come into its own again."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Frax","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Frances  , or less commonly of   Francis ."],"variants":[{"name":"Francis","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."]},{"name":"Frances","meanings":["Feminine form of   Francis .  In the 16th century the two spellings were used indiscriminately for both sexes, the distinction in spelling not being established until the 17th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gwladus Verch Dafydd Frax was born in 1315, in Carmarthenshire, Wales, her father, Dafydd Ap Iorwerth, was 36 and her mother, Mrs. Dafydd ap Iorwerth, was 32. She married Philip ap Elidir Ddû in 1357, in Carmarthenshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. She died in 1357, in Wales, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1315–1357":"1315–1357","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1320–1425":"1320–1425","1357–1393":"1357–1393","–Male":"Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1284–Female":"1284–Surnud","1315":"1315","1425":"1425","1357":"1357","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1284":"1284","1393":"1393","1280":"1280","Wales":"Wales","Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1315–1357":"1315–1357","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1320–1425":"1320–1425","1357–1393":"1357–1393","–Male":"Kuollut","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1284–Female":"1284–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1425":"1425","1357":"1357","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1284":"1284","1393":"1393","1280":"1280","Wales":"Wales","Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llandilofawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1315–1357":"1315–1357","1300–Female":"1300–Décédée","1320–1425":"1320–1425","1357–1393":"1357–1393","–Male":"Décédé","1280–Male":"1280–Décédé","1284–Female":"1284–Décédée","1315":"1315","1425":"1425","1357":"1357","1300":"1300","1320":"1320","1284":"1284","1393":"1393","1280":"1280","Wales":"Galles","